# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed as the **154th (Lowland) Regiment, RCT (Volunteers)** in Glasgow in 1967.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The initially comprised just 221 Squadron and 222 Squadron.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 527 Squadron, 230 Squadron and 231 Squadron and 251 Squadron were added on amalgamation with 153 (Highland) Transport Regiment to form the **Scottish Transport Regiment** in 1993.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 231 Squadron was subsequently disbanded.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] It became **154 (Scottish) Regiment RLC** under the Army 2020 reforms and an extra squadron, 239 Squadron, was formed in 2016.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment wears the Tactical Recognition Flash of the Royal Logistic Corps.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The tartan of the regiment is a version (designated "Government No.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 16") of the main MacDuff tartan, but with a smaller green area, worn by unit's pipers and drummers; in regular uniform, it is only used for the diamond-shaped cockade backing the badge on the uniform cap.
[src:scotland/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] A tartan was created in 2018 (approved in 2020) in honour of the Royal Logistic Corps, but this is for civilian use and is a fundraiser for the RLC's MOD Benevolent fund; it is not used for regimental uniform.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The **rugby union match played between Scotland and England** on 27 March 1871 was the world's first international rugby match.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] It is also officially the first international football match in any football code.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The match was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh in front of 4,000 spectators.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Scotland won the match, scoring two tries and a goal to England's single try.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The match resulted from a challenge issued in the sporting weekly *Bell's Weekly* on 8 December 1870 and signed by the captains of five Scottish clubs, inviting any team "selected from the whole of England" to a 20-a-side game to be played under the rugby rules.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The game was played at Raeburn Place, Edinburgh, the home ground of Edinburgh Academicals, on 27 March 1871.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The English team wore all white, with a red rose on its shirts and the Scots, brown shirts with a thistle and white cricket flannels.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The team representing England was captained by Frederick Stokes of Blackheath; that representing Scotland was led by Francis Moncrieff. the umpires were Hely Hutchinson Almond, headmaster of Loretto School in Scotland, and A.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The matches for this season were decided on goals scored.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] A goal was awarded for a successful conversion after a try, for a dropped goal or for a goal from mark.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] If a game was drawn, any unconverted tries were tallied to give a winner.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] If there was still no clear winner, the match was declared a draw.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] The game, played over two halves, each of 50 minutes, was won by Scotland, who scored a goal with a successful conversion kick after grounding the ball over the goal line (permitting them to "try" to kick a goal).
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Both sides achieved a further "try" each, but failed to convert them to goals, as the kicks were unsuccessful.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] Angus Buchanan was the first man to score a try in international rugby.
[src:scotland/1871-scotland-versus-england-rugby-union-match] In a return match at the Kennington Oval, London, in 1872, England were the winners.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] The **1970 British Commonwealth Games** were held in Edinburgh, Scotland, from 16 to 25 July 1970.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] This was the first time the name British Commonwealth Games was adopted, the first time metric units rather than imperial units were used in all events, and also the first time the event was held in Scotland.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] Also, the event saw the first unique Games trademark logo: an emblem showing the Games emblem intertwined with a St Andrews Cross and a thistle.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] The event was followed by the 1970 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] The 1970 Games was one of the most successful in the history of the event.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] In August 1966, the bid vote was held in Jamaica.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] The successful bidder was Edinburgh, Scotland with 18 votes beating Christchurch, New Zealand, with 11.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] In 1967, an appeal fund was launched, aiming to raise £200,000 towards the cost of running the games.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] 42 teams were represented at the 1970 Games.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] The Meadowbank Sports Centre was built for the 1970 Commonwealth Games, at a cost of £2.8 million.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] It was opened by Prince Edward, Duke of Kent on 2 May 1970.
[src:scotland/1970-british-commonwealth-games] Adjacent to the main stadium were three sports halls for the fencing, badminton and wrestling competitions and a velodrome built at the cost of £90,000.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A post-legislative referendum was held in Scotland in 1979 to decide whether there was sufficient support among the Scottish electorate for a Scottish Assembly proposed in the Scotland Act 1978.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was an act to create a devolved deliberative assembly for Scotland.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A majority (51.6%) of voters supported the proposal, but an amendment to the Act stipulated that it would be repealed if less than 40% of the total electorate voted in favour.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] As there was a turnout of 64% the "Yes" vote represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate, and the act was subsequently repealed.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A second referendum to create a devolved legislature in Scotland was held in 1997 under a newly elected Labour government, which led to the enactment of the Scotland Act 1998 and the creation of a devolved Scottish Parliament in 1999.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The royal commission was intended to look at the constitutional structure of the United Kingdom and consider changes that should be made.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The commission examined various models of devolution, federalism and confederalism, on top of the break-up of the UK into separate sovereign states.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In relation to Scotland, eight of the commission's members supported a Scottish Assembly, via a devolved structure.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It would recommend that the assembly would have around 100 members, elected under single transferable vote from multi-member constituencies.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The assembly would obtain powers in the areas of education, environment, health, home affairs, legal matters and social services, while agriculture, fisheries and food would be divided between the assembly and the UK government.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After returning to power with a minority government in February 1974 election, Harold Wilson's Labour government published a white paper entitled *Democracy and Devolution: Proposals for Scotland and Wales*, published in September 1974.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The party gained a narrow majority of three seats in the election in October.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] By 1976, the Labour government, now led by James Callaghan, had lost its parliamentary majority entirely following a series of adverse by-election results.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The *Scotland and Wales Bill* was subsequently introduced in November 1976, but the government struggled to get the legislation through parliament.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Conservative opposition opposed its second reading, and on the first day of committee 350 amendments were put down.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In February 1977, the Bill's cabinet sponsor Michael Foot tabled a guillotine motion to attempt to halt the delays.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The motion was rejected and the government was forced to withdraw the Bill.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government returned to the issue of devolution in November 1977.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Separate bills for Scotland and Wales were published and support from the Liberals was obtained.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In spite of continued opposition requiring another guillotine motion, the Bills were passed.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] During the passage of the Scotland Act 1978 through Parliament, an amendment introduced by Labour MP George Cunningham added a requirement that the bill had to be approved by 40% of the total registered electorate, as well as a simple majority (50% + 1).
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The sample was made up of voters in Scotland and Wales.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Number of people who said they did not vote.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The result was a majority in favour of devolution.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] A total of 1,230,937 (51.6%) voted at the referendum in favour of an Assembly, a majority of about 77,400 over those voting against.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] However, this total represented only 32.9% of the registered electorate as a whole.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The Labour government held that the Act's requirements had not been met, and that devolution would therefore not be introduced for Scotland.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In the wake of the referendum the disappointed supporters of the bill conducted a protest campaign under the slogan "Scotland said 'yes'", officially launched in a Glasgow hotel on 7 March 1979.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] In particular, the Scottish National Party (SNP) carried out a survey of the electoral register in the Edinburgh Central constituency.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This appeared to show that the register was so out of date that even in an area where major support for a "yes" vote might be expected, achievement of 40% of the electorate was virtually unattainable.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was because the majority of electors lived in older tenements or newer Council blocks of flats where flat numbers were not specified.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The work of electoral registration staff to obtain an accurate current register was almost impossible.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] Under the terms of the Act, it could then be repealed by a Statutory instrument to be approved by Parliament.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government's decision to abandon devolution led the SNP to withdraw its support for the Labour government.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] It was in a minority in Parliament and had relied on deals with the smaller parties, including the SNP, for its survival.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] After establishing that the Liberals and the SNP would vote against the government in a confidence motion, the Conservative opposition tabled a motion on 28 March.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] The government was defeated by one vote, and a UK general election was subsequently called.
[src:scotland/1979-scottish-devolution-referendum] This was won by the Conservatives, and Parliament voted to repeal the Act on 20 June 1979.
[src:scotland/gb] The domain was introduced with RFC 920 in October 1984 that set out the creation of ccTLD generally using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:scotland/gb] However, the .uk domain had been created separately a few months before the compilation of this list.
[src:scotland/gb] Consequently, .gb was never widely used.
[src:scotland/gb] It is no longer possible to register under this domain.
[src:scotland/gb] .gb was used for a number of years, mainly by British government organisations and commercial e-mail services using X.400-based e-mail infrastructure.
[src:scotland/gb] This simplified translating between DNS domains and X.400 addresses, which used "GB" as a country code.
[src:scotland/gb] With the demise of X.400 e-mail and IANA's general aim of one TLD per country, use of .gb declined; the domain remains in existence, but it is not currently open to new domain registrations.
[src:scotland/gb] As of 2025, there are at least three subdomains resolving through DNS (although none serve a web page or use): `hermes.dra.hmg.gb`, `delos.dra.hmg.gb`, and `dfhnet.dra.hmg.gb`.
[src:scotland/gb] They were originally owned by the Defence Research Agency, which became the Defence Evaluation and Research Agency in 1995 and was split into QinetiQ and the Defence Science and Technology Laboratory in 2001; the websites became defunct some time thereafter.
[src:scotland/gb] As of November 2022, Central Digital and Data Office's intention was to inform ICANN early in 2023 that the UK wishes to retire the .gb ccTLD.
[src:scotland/scot] Originally, *.sco* was proposed in a campaign.
[src:scotland/scot] In 2008 dotCYMRU, dotEUS, dotSCOT and dotBZH formed ECLID.
[src:scotland/scot] Later it was decided to allow newly proposed top-level domains for introduction some time in 2013, and a list of applications for these was published in June 2012; the domain .scot was included.
[src:scotland/scot] On 27 January 2014, dotScot Registry, a not-for-profit organisation established in 2009, announced that it had agreed terms to operate the .scot domain name, with plans to get it up and running later in summer of 2014.
[src:scotland/scot] On 15 July 2014, .scot was officially launched.
[src:scotland/scot] The first .scot domain name to go live was calico.scot, registered by hosting company Calico Internet Ltd.
[src:scotland/scot] On 17 February 2015, the Scottish Government migrated its website from Scotland.gov.uk to gov.scot.
[src:scotland/scot] Likewise, the Scottish Parliament moved from Scottish.parliament.uk to parliament.scot in May 2016, to coincide with the 2016 elections.
[src:scotland/scot] The 2017 Global Amendment to the base New GeoTLD Registry Agreement is effective as of 31 July 2017.
[src:scotland/scot] On 3 May 2018 the dotScot Registry lifted registration restrictions on locality domains (based on towns, etc.) and other premium names.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland emerged as a sovereign state in the 9th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Independence from England was maintained partly through an alliance with France.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1603, James VI succeeded to the thrones of England and Ireland, forming a personal union of the three kingdoms.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] On 1 May 1707, Scotland and England combined to create the new Kingdom of Great Britain, with the Parliament of Scotland subsumed into the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1999, a Scottish Parliament was re-established, and has devolved authority over many areas of domestic policy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The country has its own distinct legal system, education system and religious history, which have all contributed to the continuation of Scottish culture and national identity.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scottish English and Scots are the most widely spoken languages in the country, existing on a dialect continuum with each other.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The mainland of Scotland is broadly divided into three regions: the Highlands, a mountainous region in the north and north-west; the Lowlands, a flatter plain across the centre of the country; and the Southern Uplands, a hilly region along the southern border.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Highlands are the most mountainous region of the British Isles and contain its highest peak, Ben Nevis, at 4,413 feet (1,345 m).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The region also contains many lakes, called lochs; the term is also applied to the many saltwater inlets along the country's deeply indented western coastline.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The geography of the many islands is varied.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Some, such as Mull and Skye, are noted for their mountainous terrain, while Tiree and Coll are flatter.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Neolithic farmers arrived in Scotland around 6000 years ago.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The well-preserved village of Skara Brae on the mainland of Orkney dates from this period.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Neolithic habitation, burial, and ritual sites are particularly common and well preserved in the Northern Isles and Western Isles, where a lack of trees led to most structures being built of local stone.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Evidence of sophisticated pre-Christian belief systems is demonstrated by sites such as the Callanish Stones on Lewis, and the Maes Howe on Orkney, which were built in the third millennium BC.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The first written reference to Scotland was in 320 BC by Greek sailor Pytheas, who called the northern tip of Britain "Orcas", the source of the name of the Orkney islands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Most of modern Scotland was not incorporated into the Roman Empire, and Roman control over parts of the area fluctuated over a rather short period.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The first Roman incursion into Scotland was in 79 AD, when Agricola invaded Scotland; he defeated a Caledonian army at the Battle of Mons Graupius in 83 AD.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] After the Roman victory, Roman forts were briefly set along the Gask Ridge close to the Highland line, but by three years after the battle, the Roman armies had withdrawn to the Southern Uplands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Remains of Roman forts established in the 1st century have been found as far north as the Moray Firth.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] By the reign of the Roman emperor Trajan (r.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] 98–117), Roman control had lapsed to Britain south of a line between the River Tyne and the Solway Firth.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Along this line, Trajan's successor Hadrian (r.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] 117–138) erected Hadrian's Wall in northern England and the *Limes Britannicus* became the northern border of the Roman Empire.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Roman influence on the southern part of the country was considerable, and they introduced Christianity to Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Antonine Wall was built from 142 at the order of Hadrian's successor Antoninus Pius (r.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] 138–161), defending the Roman part of Scotland from the unadministered part of the island, north of a line between the Firth of Clyde and the Firth of Forth.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] 193–211) at Eboracum (York) after he was taken ill while on campaign.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Although forts erected by the Roman army in the Severan campaign were placed near those established by Agricola and were clustered at the mouths of the glens in the Highlands, the Caledonians were again in revolt in 210–211 and these were overrun.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] To the Roman historians Tacitus and Cassius Dio, the Scottish Highlands and the area north of the River Forth was called Caledonia.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] According to Cassius Dio, the inhabitants of Caledonia were the Caledonians and the Maeatae.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The name Caledonia is echoed in the place names of Dunkeld, Rohallion, and Schiehallion.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Great Conspiracy constituted a seemingly coordinated invasion against Roman rule in Britain in the later 4th century, which included the participation of the Gaelic Scoti and the Caledonians, who were then known as Picts by the Romans.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] This was defeated by the *comes* Theodosius; but Roman military government was withdrawn from the island altogether by the early 5th century, resulting in the Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain and the immigration of the Saxons to southeastern Scotland and the rest of eastern Great Britain.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] These societies were based on the family unit and had sharp divisions in wealth, although the vast majority were poor and worked full-time in subsistence agriculture.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Picts kept slaves (mostly captured in war) through the ninth century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Gaelic influence over Pictland and Northumbria was facilitated by the large number of Gaelic-speaking clerics working as missionaries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Operating in the sixth century on the island of Iona, Saint Columba was one of the earliest and best-known missionaries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Vikings began to raid Scotland in the eighth century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Although the raiders sought slaves and luxury items, their main motivation was to acquire land.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The oldest Norse settlements were in northwest Scotland, but they eventually conquered many areas along the coast.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Old Norse entirely displaced Pictish in the Northern Isles.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In the ninth century, the Norse threat allowed a Gael named Kenneth I (Cináed mac Ailpín) to seize power over Pictland, establishing a royal dynasty to which the modern monarchs trace their lineage, and marking the beginning of the end of Pictish culture.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The kingdom of Cináed and his descendants, called Alba, was Gaelic in character but existed on the same area as Pictland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] By the end of the tenth century, the Pictish language went extinct as its speakers shifted to Gaelic.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] From a base in eastern Scotland north of the River Forth and south of the River Spey, the kingdom expanded first southwards, into the former Northumbrian lands, and northwards into Moray.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, there was a centralization in agricultural lands and the first towns began to be established.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, much of Scotland was under the control of a single ruler.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Initially, Gaelic culture predominated, but immigrants from France, England and Flanders steadily created a more diverse society, with the Gaelic language starting to be replaced by Scots; and a modern nation-state emerged from this.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] At the end of this period, war against England started the growth of a Scottish national consciousness.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] David I (1124–1153) and his successors centralised royal power and united mainland Scotland, capturing regions such as Moray, Galloway, and Caithness, although he could not extend his power over the Hebrides, which had been ruled by various Scottish clans following the death of Somerled in 1164.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1266, Scotland fought the short but consequential Scottish-Norwegian War which saw the reclamation of the Hebrides after the strong defeat of King Haakon IV and his forces at the Battle of Largs.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] After the conflict, Scotland had to affirm Norwegian sovereignty of the Northern Isles, but they were later integrated into Scotland in the 15th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scandinavian culture in the form of the Norn language survived for a lot longer than in the Hebrides, and would strongly influence the local Scots dialect on Shetland and Orkney.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Later, a system of feudalism was consolidated, with both Anglo-Norman incomers and native Gaelic chieftains being granted land in exchange for serving the king.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The relationship with England was complex during this period: Scottish kings tried several times, sometimes with success, to exploit English political turmoil, followed by the longest period of peace between Scotland and England in the mediaeval period: from 1217–1296.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The death of Alexander III in March 1286 broke the succession line of Scotland's kings.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Edward I of England arbitrated between various claimants for the Scottish crown.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In return for surrendering Scotland's nominal independence, John Balliol was pronounced king in 1292.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1294, Balliol and other Scottish lords refused Edward's demands to serve in his army against the French.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland and France sealed a treaty on 23 October 1295, known as the Auld Alliance.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] War ensued, and John was deposed by Edward who took personal control of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Andrew Moray and William Wallace initially emerged as the principal leaders of the resistance to English rule in the Wars of Scottish Independence, until Robert the Bruce was crowned king of Scotland in 1306.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Victory at the Battle of Bannockburn in 1314 proved the Scots had regained control of their kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1320 the world's first documented declaration of independence, the Declaration of Arbroath, won the support of Pope John XXII, leading to the legal recognition of Scottish sovereignty by the English Crown.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] A civil war between the Bruce dynasty and their long-term rivals of the House of Comyn and House of Balliol lasted until the middle of the 14th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Although the Bruce faction was successful, David II's lack of an heir allowed his half-nephew Robert II, the Lord High Steward of Scotland, to come to the throne and establish the House of Stewart.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Stewarts ruled Scotland for the remainder of the Middle Ages.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The country they ruled experienced greater prosperity from the end of the 14th century through the Scottish Renaissance to the Reformation, despite the effects of the Black Death in 1349 and increasing division between Highlands and Lowlands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Multiple truces reduced warfare on the southern border.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Treaty of Perpetual Peace was signed in 1502 by James IV of Scotland and Henry VII of England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] James married Henry's daughter, Margaret Tudor.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] James invaded England in support of France under the terms of the Auld Alliance and became the last monarch in Great Britain to die in battle, at Flodden in 1513.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The war with England during the minority years of Mary, Queen of Scots between 1543 and 1551 is known as the Rough Wooing.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1560, the Treaty of Edinburgh brought an end to the Siege of Leith and recognized the Protestant Elizabeth I as Queen of England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Parliament of Scotland met and immediately adopted the Scots Confession, which signalled the Scottish Reformation's sharp break from papal authority and Roman Catholic teaching.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Catholic Mary, Queen of Scots, was forced to abdicate in 1567.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1603, James VI, King of Scots inherited the thrones of the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Ireland in the Union of the Crowns, and moved to London.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] This was a personal union as despite having the same monarch the kingdoms retained their separate parliaments, laws and other institutions.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The first Union Jack was designed at James's behest, to be flown in addition to the St Andrew's Cross on Scots vessels at sea.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Except for a short period under the Protectorate, Scotland remained a separate state in the 17th century, but there was considerable conflict between the crown and the Covenanters over the form of church government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The military was strengthened, allowing the imposition of royal authority on the western Highland clans.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The 1609 Statutes of Iona compelled the cultural integration of Hebridean clan leaders.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1641 and again in 1643, the Parliament of Scotland unsuccessfully sought a union with England which was "federative" and not "incorporating", in which Scotland would retain a separate parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The issue of union split the parliament in 1648.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Protectorate Parliament was the first Westminster parliament to include representatives nominally from Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The monarchy of the House of Stuart was resumed with the Restoration in Scotland in 1660.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Parliament of Scotland sought a commercial union with England in 1664; the proposal was rejected in 1668.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1670 the Parliament of England rejected a proposed political union with Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] English proposals along the same lines were abandoned in 1674 and in 1685.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Scots Parliament rejected proposals for a political union with England in 1689.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Jacobitism, the political support for the exiled Catholic Stuart dynasty, remained a threat to the security of the British state under the Protestant House of Orange and the succeeding House of Hanover until the defeat of the Jacobite rising of 1745.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 1698, the Company of Scotland attempted a project to secure a trading colony on the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Almost every Scottish landowner who had money to spare is said to have invested in the Darien scheme.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] After another proposal from the English House of Lords was rejected in 1695, and a further Lords motion was voted down in the House of Commons in 1700, the Parliament of Scotland again rejected union in 1702.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The failure of the Darien Scheme bankrupted the landowners who had invested, though not the burghs.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Nevertheless, the nobles' bankruptcy, along with the threat of an English invasion, played a leading role in convincing the Scots elite to back a union with England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] On 22 July 1706, the Treaty of Union was agreed between representatives of the Scots Parliament and the Parliament of England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The following year, twin Acts of Union were passed by both parliaments to create the united Kingdom of Great Britain with effect from 1 May 1707 with popular opposition and anti-union riots in Edinburgh, Glasgow, and elsewhere.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The union also created the Parliament of Great Britain, which succeeded both the Parliament of Scotland and the Parliament of England, which rejected proposals from the Parliament of Ireland that the third kingdom be incorporated in the union.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The deposed Jacobite Stuart claimants had remained popular in the Highlands and north-east, particularly among non-Presbyterians, including Roman Catholics and Episcopalian Protestants.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Two major Jacobite risings launched in 1715 and 1745 failed to remove the House of Hanover from the British throne.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The threat of the Jacobite movement to the United Kingdom and its monarchs effectively ended at the Battle of Culloden, Great Britain's last pitched battle.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The passing of the Treaty of Union did not bring about immediate economic prosperity to Scotland as was widely speculated by the pamphleteer as a result of the little consideration given to prospects of the Scottish economy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Campaigners for the union between Scotland and England believed that there would be economic advantages to Scotland as a result of the failed Darien scheme which left the Kingdom of Scotland bankrupt.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Eventually however, with trade tariffs with England abolished, trade blossomed, especially with Colonial America.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The clippers belonging to the Glasgow Tobacco Lords were the fastest ships on the route to Virginia.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Until the American War of Independence in 1776, Glasgow was the world's premier tobacco port, dominating world trade.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The disparity between the wealth of the merchant classes of the Scottish Lowlands and the ancient clans of the Scottish Highlands grew, amplifying centuries of division.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In the Highlands, clan chiefs gradually started to think of themselves more as commercial landlords than leaders of their people.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] These social and economic changes included the first phase of the Highland Clearances and, ultimately, the demise of clanship.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Scottish Reform Act 1832 increased the number of Scottish MPs and widened the franchise to include more of the middle classes.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] From the mid-century, there were increasing calls for Home Rule for Scotland and the post of Secretary of State for Scotland was revived.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Towards the end of the century prime ministers of Scottish descent included William Gladstone, and the Earl of Rosebery.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In the late 19th century the growing importance of the working classes was marked by Keir Hardie's success in the Mid Lanarkshire by-election, 1888, leading to the foundation of the Scottish Labour Party, which was absorbed into the Independent Labour Party in 1895, with Hardie as its first leader.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Glasgow became one of the largest cities in the world and known as "the Second City of the Empire" after London.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] After 1860, the Clydeside shipyards specialised in steamships made of iron (after 1870, made of steel), which rapidly replaced the wooden sailing vessels of both the merchant fleets and the battle fleets of the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It became the world's pre-eminent shipbuilding centre.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In literature, the most successful figure of the mid-19th century was Walter Scott.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] His first prose work, *Waverley* in 1814, is often called the first historical novel.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It launched a highly successful career that probably more than any other helped define and popularise Scottish cultural identity.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In the late 19th century, a number of Scottish-born authors achieved international reputations, such as Robert Louis Stevenson, Arthur Conan Doyle, J.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland also played a major part in the development of art and architecture.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Proponents included architect and artist Charles Rennie Mackintosh.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland played a major role in the British effort in the First World War.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It especially provided manpower, ships, machinery, fish and money.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] With a population of 4.8 million in 1911, Scotland sent over half a million men to the war, of whom over a quarter died in combat or from disease, and 150,000 were seriously wounded.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Field Marshal Sir Douglas Haig was Britain's commander on the Western Front.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The war saw the emergence of a radical movement called "Red Clydeside" led by militant trades unionists.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Formerly a Liberal stronghold, the industrial districts switched to Labour by 1922, with a base among the Irish Catholic working-class districts.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Women were especially active in building neighbourhood solidarity on housing issues.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The "Reds" operated within the Labour Party with little influence in Parliament and the mood changed to passive despair by the late 1920s.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] During the Second World War, Scotland was targeted by Nazi Germany largely due to its factories, shipyards, and coal mines.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Cities such as Glasgow and Edinburgh were targeted by German bombers, as were smaller towns mostly located in the central belt of the country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Perhaps the most significant air raid in Scotland was the Clydebank Blitz of March 1941, which intended to destroy naval shipbuilding in the area.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] 528 people were killed and 4,000 homes destroyed.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Perhaps Scotland's most unusual wartime episode occurred in 1941 when Rudolf Hess flew to Renfrewshire, possibly intending to broker a peace deal through the Duke of Hamilton.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Before his departure from Germany, Hess had given his adjutant, Karlheinz Pintsch, a letter addressed to Adolf Hitler that detailed his intentions to open peace negotiations with the British.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Pintsch delivered the letter to Hitler at the Berghof around noon on 11 May.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Albert Speer later said Hitler described Hess's departure as one of the worst personal blows of his life, as he considered it a personal betrayal.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Hitler worried that his allies, Italy and Japan, would perceive Hess's act as an attempt by Hitler to secretly open peace negotiations with the British.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] After 1945, Scotland's economic situation worsened due to overseas competition, inefficient industry, and industrial disputes.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Only in recent decades has the country enjoyed something of a cultural and economic renaissance.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Economic factors contributing to this recovery included a resurgent financial services industry, electronics manufacturing, (see Silicon Glen), and the North Sea oil and gas industry.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The introduction in 1989 by Margaret Thatcher's government of the Community Charge (widely known as the Poll Tax) one year before the rest of Great Britain, contributed to a growing movement for Scottish control over domestic affairs.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] On 21 December 1988, Pan Am Flight 103 exploded mid–air over the town of Lockerbie, killing all on board as well as eleven Lockerbie residents.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It remains the deadliest terrorist attack in the United Kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Following a referendum on devolution proposals in 1997, the Scotland Act 1998 was passed by the British Parliament, which established a devolved Scottish Parliament and Scottish Government with responsibility for most laws specific to Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Scottish Parliament was reconvened in Edinburgh on 4 July 1999.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The first to hold the office of first minister of Scotland was Donald Dewar, who served until his sudden death in 2000.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Scottish Parliament Building at Holyrood opened in October 2004 after lengthy construction delays and running over budget.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Scottish Parliament's form of proportional representation (the additional member system) resulted in no one party having an overall majority for the first three Scottish parliament elections.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The pro-independence Scottish National Party led by Alex Salmond achieved an overall majority in the 2011 election, winning 69 of the 129 seats available.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The success of the SNP in achieving a majority in the Scottish Parliament paved the way for the September 2014 referendum on Scottish independence.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The majority voted against the proposition, with 55% voting no to independence.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] More powers, particularly concerning taxation, were devolved to the Scottish Parliament after the referendum, following cross-party talks in the Smith Commission.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Since the 2014 referendum, events such as the UK leaving the European Union, despite a majority of voters in Scotland voting to remain a member, have led to calls for a second independence referendum.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 2022, the Lord Advocate Dorothy Bain argued the case for the Scottish Government to hold another referendum on the issue, with the Supreme Court later ruling against the argument.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Following the Supreme Court decision, the Scottish Government stated that it wished to make amendments to the Scotland Act 1998 that would allow a referendum to be held.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The mainland of Scotland comprises the northern third of the land mass of the island of Great Britain, which lies off the northwest coast of Continental Europe.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The total area is 30,977 square miles (80,231 km2) with a land area of 30,078 square miles (77,901 km2), comparable to the size of the Czech Republic.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland's only land border is with England, and runs for 96 miles (154 km) between the basin of the River Tweed on the east coast and the Solway Firth in the west.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Atlantic Ocean borders the west coast and the North Sea is to the east.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The island of Ireland lies only 13 miles (21 km) from the south-western peninsula of Kintyre; Norway is 190 miles (305 km) to the northeast and the Faroe Islands, 168 miles (270 km) to the north.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The territorial extent of Scotland is generally that established by the 1237 Treaty of York between Scotland and the Kingdom of England and the 1266 Treaty of Perth between Scotland and Norway.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The geographical centre of Scotland lies a few miles from the village of Newtonmore in Badenoch.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Rising to 4,413 feet (1,345 m) above sea level, Scotland's highest point is the summit of Ben Nevis, in Lochaber, while Scotland's longest river, the River Tay, flows for a distance of 117 miles (188 km).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland has an estimated 900 islands of which roughly 118 are uninhabited.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The islands are divided into four main groups: Shetland, Orkney, the Inner Hebrides and the Outer Hebrides.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The country has the majority of the largest islands in the British Isles, with 71 with an area of at least 5 km2 (1.9 sq mi).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The largest island is Lewis and Harris, followed by Skye, the Shetland mainland and Mull.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Lewis and Harris also has the largest population of any island in the British Isles, with a population of 21,574 in 2011.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Smaller islands by population include Arran, Bute, South Uist, Islay and Great Cumbrae which have populations between 1,300 and 6,400.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Ailsa Craig, which lies off the coast of South Ayrshire, has no permanent population.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It is known as a source for microgranite, which is used to make curling stones.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Off the northern coast of the mainland lie Shetland and Orkney, two island groups which, despite being part of Scotland since 1472, have retained elements of their own culture and identify.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] They were acquired by James III of Scotland following King Christian I of Denmark's decision to relinquish the islands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Shetland and Orkney are governed by their own administrative councils and both act as one of the 32 administrative areas of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Rockall is a small rocky islet in the North Atlantic which was declared part of Scotland by the Island of Rockall Act 1972.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Despite no possession by any other state or other precedents, the legality of the claim is disputed by the Republic of Ireland, Denmark and Iceland, and may be unenforceable in international law.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The whole of Scotland was covered by ice sheets during the Pleistocene ice ages and the landscape is much affected by glaciation.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] From a geological perspective, the country has three main sub-divisions: the Highlands and Islands, the Central Lowlands, and the Southern Uplands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Highlands and Islands lie to the north and west of the Highland Boundary Fault, which runs from Arran to Stonehaven.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] This part of Scotland largely comprises ancient rocks from the Cambrian and Precambrian, which were uplifted during the later Caledonian orogeny.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] It is interspersed with igneous intrusions of a more recent age, remnants of which formed mountain massifs such as the Cairngorms and the Cuillin.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In north-eastern mainland Scotland weathering of rock that occurred before the Last Ice Age has shaped much of the landscape.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] A significant exception to the above are the fossil-bearing beds of Old Red Sandstones found principally along the Moray Firth coast.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Highlands are generally mountainous and the highest elevations in the British Isles are found here.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] There are numerous bodies of freshwater including Loch Lomond and Loch Ness.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Some parts of the coastline consist of machair, a low-lying dune pasture land.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Central Lowlands is a rift valley mainly comprising Paleozoic formations.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Many of these sediments have economic significance, for it is here that the coal and iron-bearing rocks that fuelled Scotland's industrial revolution are found.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] This area has also experienced intense volcanism, Arthur's Seat in Edinburgh being the remnant of a once much larger volcano.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] This area is relatively low-lying, although even here hills such as the Ochils and Campsie Fells are rarely far from view.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Southern Uplands is a range of hills almost 125 miles (200 km) long, interspersed with broad valleys.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] They lie south of a second fault line (the Southern Uplands fault) that runs from Girvan to Dunbar.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The geological foundations largely comprise Silurian deposits laid down some 400 to 500 million years ago.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The high point of the Southern Uplands is Merrick with an elevation of 843 m (2,766 ft).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The Southern Uplands is home to Scotland's highest village, Wanlockhead (430 m or 1,411 ft above sea level).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The climate of most of Scotland is temperate and oceanic, and tends to be very changeable.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] As it is warmed by the Gulf Stream from the Atlantic, it has much milder winters (but cooler, wetter summers) than areas on similar latitudes, such as Labrador, southern Scandinavia, the Moscow region in Russia, and the Kamchatka Peninsula on the opposite side of Eurasia.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Temperatures are generally lower than in the rest of the UK, with the temperature of −27.2 °C (−17.0 °F) recorded at Braemar in the Grampian Mountains, on 11 February 1895, the coldest ever recorded anywhere in the UK.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The same temperature was also recorded in Braemar on 10 January 1982 and at Altnaharra, Highland, on 30 December 1995.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Winter maxima average 6 °C (43 °F) in the lowlands, with summer maxima averaging 18 °C (64 °F).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The highest temperature recorded was 34.8 °C (94.6 °F) at Charterhall, Scottish Borders on 19 July 2022.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The west of Scotland is usually warmer than the east, owing to the influence of Atlantic ocean currents and the colder surface temperatures of the North Sea.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Tiree, in the Inner Hebrides, is one of the sunniest places in the country: it had more than 300 hours of sunshine in May 1975.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The western Highlands of Scotland are the wettest, with annual rainfall in a few places exceeding 3,000 mm (120 in).
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In comparison, much of lowland Scotland receives less than 800 mm (31 in) annually.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Heavy snowfall is not common in the Lowlands, but becomes more common with altitude.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Braemar has an average of 59 snow days per year, while many coastal areas average fewer than 10 days of lying snow per year.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Climate change is expected to have a significant impact on Scotland; if the world warms by 3 degrees, it could cost up to 8% of the GDP of the United Kingdom by 2070.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Between 1990 and 2023, Scotland reduced its greenhouse gas emissions by 51.3%.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] In 2026 it adopted a climate change plan with the goal of becoming carbon neutral by 2045.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The plan includes making heating houses carbon-free by 2045, covering 21% of the country by forests by 2032, and restoring peatlands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland's wildlife is typical of the north-west of Europe, although several of the larger mammals such as the lynx, brown bear, wolf, elk and walrus were hunted to extinction in historic times.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] There are important populations of seals and internationally significant nesting grounds for a variety of seabirds such as gannets.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The golden eagle is something of a national icon.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] On the high mountain tops, species including ptarmigan, mountain hare and stoat can be seen in their white colour phase during winter months.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Remnants of the native Scots pine forest exist and within these areas the Scottish crossbill, the UK's only endemic bird species and vertebrate, can be found alongside capercaillie, Scottish wildcat, red squirrel and pine marten.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Various animals have been re-introduced, including the white-tailed eagle in 1975, the red kite in the 1980s, and there have been experimental projects involving the beaver and wild boar, which are both now relatively widespread.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Today, much of the remaining native Caledonian Forest lies within the Cairngorms National Park and remnants of the forest remain at 84 locations across Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] On the west coast, remnants of ancient Celtic Rainforest remain, particularly on the Taynish peninsula in Argyll, these forests are particularly rare due to high rates of deforestation throughout Scottish history.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Scotland now ranks in the lowest 15% of countries in the Biodiversity Intactness Index.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The flora of the country is varied incorporating both deciduous and coniferous woodland as well as moorland and tundra species.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Large-scale commercial tree planting and management of upland moorland habitat for the grazing of sheep and field sport activities like deer stalking and driven grouse shooting impacts the distribution of indigenous plants and animals.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] The UK's tallest tree is a grand fir planted beside Loch Fyne, Argyll in the 1870s, and the Fortingall Yew may be 5,000 years old and is probably the oldest living thing in Europe.
[src:scotland/scotland-p01] Although the number of native vascular plants is low by world standards, Scotland's substantial bryophyte flora is of global importance.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland is part of the United Kingdom, a constitutional monarchy whose current sovereign is Charles III.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The monarchy uses a variety of styles, titles and other symbols specific to Scotland, most of which originated in the pre–union Kingdom of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] These include the Royal Standard of Scotland, the royal coat of arms, and the title Duke of Rothesay, which is traditionally given to the heir apparent.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There are also distinct Scottish Officers of State and Officers of the Crown, and the Order of the Thistle, a chivalric order, is specific to the country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Parliament of the United Kingdom and the Parliament of Scotland are the country's primary legislative bodies.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The UK Parliament is sovereign and therefore has supremacy over the Scottish Parliament, but generally restricts itself to legislating over reserved matters: primarily some taxes, some aspects of social security, defence, international relations, and broadcasting.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There is a convention that the UK Parliament will not legislate over devolved matters without the Scottish Parliament's consent.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland is represented in the House of Commons, the lower chamber of the UK Parliament, by 57 Members of Parliament (out of a total of 650).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] They are elected to single-member constituencies under the first-past-the-post system of voting.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scotland Office represents the British government in Scotland and represents Scottish interests within the government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scotland Office is led by the secretary of state for Scotland, who sits in the Cabinet of the United Kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Labour MP Douglas Alexander has held the position since September 2025, replacing the Ian Murray, who had served from July 2024.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Parliament is a unicameral legislature with 129 members (MSPs): 73 of them represent individual constituencies and are elected on a first-past-the-post system, and the other 56 are elected in eight different electoral regions by the additional member system.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] MSPs normally serve for a five-year period.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Parliament has the most extensive devolved powers amongst the devolved parliaments in the United Kingdom, and considered one of the most powerful devolved parliaments internationally.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The largest party since the 2021 Scottish Parliament election, has been the Scottish National Party (SNP), which won 64 of the 129 seats.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Conservatives, Scottish Labour, the Scottish Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens also have representation in the current Parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The next Scottish Parliament election is due to be held in 2031.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Government, which has been described as one of the most powerful devolved governments globally, is led by the first minister, who is nominated by MSPs and is typically the leader of the largest party in the Parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Other ministers are appointed by the first minister and serve at their discretion.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As the head of the Scottish Government, the first minister is responsible for the comprehensive development, implementation and presentation of government policy, and is responsible for promoting the interests of the country at home and internationally.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] John Swinney, leader of the Scottish National Party (SNP), has served as the first minister since 8 May 2024.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As leader of the Scottish Government, the first minister is a member of the Prime Minister and Heads of Devolved Governments Council and the Council of the Nations and Regions, the bodies which facilitate intergovernmental relations within the United Kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Foreign policy is a reserved matter and primarily the responsibility of the Foreign Office, a department of the UK Government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Nevertheless, the Scottish Government may promote Scottish interests abroad and encourage foreign investment in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The first minister and the constitution secretary have portfolios which include foreign affairs.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's international network consists of two Scotland Houses, one in Brussels and the other in London, seven Scottish Government international offices, and over thirty Scottish Development International offices in other countries globally.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Both Scotland Houses are independent Scottish Government establishments, whilst the seven Scottish Government international offices are based in British embassies or British High Commission offices.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Government has a network of offices in Beijing, Berlin, Brussels, Copenhagen, Dublin, London, Ottawa, Paris, and Washington, D.C., which promote Scottish interests in their respective areas.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Additionally, the country has a number of foreign diplomatic missions, most of which are located in the capital city, Edinburgh.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The nation has historic ties to France as a result of the 'Auld Alliance', a treaty signed between the Kingdom of Scotland and Kingdom of France in 1295 to discourage an English invasion of either country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The alliance effectively ended in the sixteenth century, but the two countries continue to have a close relationship, with a Statement of Intent being signed in 2013 between the Scottish Government and the Government of France.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland also has historical and cultural ties with the Scandinavian countries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scottish Government policy advocates for stronger political relations with the Nordic and Baltic countries, which has resulted in some Nordic-inspired policies being adopted such as baby boxes.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Representatives from the Scottish Parliament attended the Nordic Council for the first time in 2022.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland held the Presidency of Conference of European Regions with Legislative Power from November 2003 until November 2004 during the premiership of Jack McConnell.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Devolution—the granting of central government powers to a regional government– gained increasing popularity as a policy in the United Kingdom in the late twentieth century; it was described by John Smith, then Leader of the Labour Party, as the "settled will of the Scottish people".
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Parliament and Scottish Government were subsequently established under the Scotland Act 1998; the Act followed a successful referendum in 1997 which found majority support for both creating the Parliament and granting it limited powers to vary income tax.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Act enabled the new institutions to legislate in all areas not explicitly reserved by the UK Parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Two more pieces of legislation, the Scotland Acts of 2012 and 2016, gave the Scottish Parliament further powers to legislate on taxation and social security; the 2016 Act also gave the Scottish Government powers to manage the affairs of the Crown Estate in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Conversely, the United Kingdom Internal Market Act 2020 constrains the Scottish Parliament's autonomy to regulate goods and services, and the academic view is that this undermines devolution.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The 2007 Scottish Parliament elections led to the Scottish National Party (SNP), which supports Scottish independence, forming a minority government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The new government established a "National Conversation" on constitutional issues, proposing a number of options such as increasing the powers of the Scottish Parliament, federalism, or a referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The three main unionist opposition parties–Scottish Labour, the Scottish Conservatives, and the Scottish Liberal Democrats–created a separate commission to investigate the distribution of powers between devolved Scottish and UK-wide bodies while not considering independence.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In August 2009 the SNP proposed a bill to hold a referendum on independence in November 2010, but was defeated by opposition from all other major parties.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The 2011 Scottish Parliament election resulted in an SNP overall majority in the Scottish Parliament, and on 18 September 2014 a referendum on Scottish independence was held.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The referendum resulted in a rejection of independence, by 55.3% to 44.7%.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] During the campaign, the three main parties in the British Parliament–the Conservatives, Labour, and the Liberal Democrats–pledged to extend the powers of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] An all-party commission chaired by Robert Smith, Baron Smith of Kelvin was formed, which led to the Scotland Act 2016.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Following the European Union Referendum Act 2015, the 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum was held on 23 June 2016 on Britain's membership of the European Union.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A majority in the United Kingdom voted to withdraw from the EU, while a majority within Scotland voted to remain a member.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The first minister, Nicola Sturgeon, announced the following day that as a result a new independence referendum was "highly likely".
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] On 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom formally withdrew from the European Union.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Because constitutional affairs are reserved matters under the Scotland Act, the Scottish Parliament would again have to be granted temporary additional powers under Section 30 to hold a legally binding vote.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] For local government purposes Scotland is subdivided into 32 single-tier council areas.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The areas were established in 1996, and their councils are responsible for the provision of all local government services.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Decisions are made by councillors, who are elected at local elections every five years.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The leader of the council is typically a councillor from the party with the most seats; councils also have a civic head, typically called the provost or lord provost, who represents the council on ceremonial occasions and chairs council meetings.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Community Councils are informal organisations that represent smaller subdivisions within each council area.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Police Scotland and the Scottish Fire and Rescue Service cover the entire country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] For healthcare and postal districts, and a number of other governmental and non-governmental organisations such as the churches, there are other long-standing methods of subdividing Scotland for the purposes of administration.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There are eight cities in Scotland: Aberdeen, Dundee, Dunfermline, Edinburgh, Glasgow, Inverness, Perth and Stirling.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] City status in the United Kingdom is conferred by the monarch through letters patent.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As one of the countries of the United Kingdom, the British Armed Forces are the armed forces of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Of the money spent on UK defence, about £3.3 billion could be attributed to Scotland in 2018–2019.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland had a long military tradition predating the Treaty of Union with England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Following the Treaty of Union in 1707, the Scots Army and Royal Scots Navy merged with their English counterparts to form the Royal Navy and the British Army, which together form part of the British Armed Forces.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Atholl Highlanders, Europe's only remaining legal private army, did not join the Scots Army or Royal Scots Navy in merging with English armed forces, remaining a private army not under the command of the British Armed Forces.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Numerous Scottish regiments have at various times existed in the British Army.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Distinctively Scottish regiments in the British Army include the Scots Guards, the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards and the 154 (Scottish) Regiment RLC, an Army Reserve regiment of the Royal Logistic Corps.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2006, as a result of the *Delivering Security in a Changing World* white paper, the Scottish infantry regiments in the Scottish Division were amalgamated to form the Royal Regiment of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As a result of the Cameron–Clegg coalition's Strategic Defence and Security Review 2010, the Scottish regiments of the line in the British Army infantry, having previously formed the Scottish Division, were reorganised into the Scottish, Welsh and Irish Division in 2017.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Before the formation of the Scottish Division, the Scottish infantry was organised into a Lowland Brigade and Highland Brigade.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Because of their topography and perceived remoteness, parts of Scotland have housed many sensitive defence establishments.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Between 1960 and 1991, the Holy Loch was a base for the US fleet of Polaris-equipped ballistic missile submarines.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Today, His Majesty's Naval Base Clyde, 25 miles (40 kilometres) north-west of Glasgow, is the base for the four Trident-armed *Vanguard*-class ballistic missile submarines that comprise the Britain's nuclear deterrent.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's Scapa Flow was the main base for the Royal Navy in the 20th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As the Cold War intensified in 1961, the United States deployed Polaris ballistic missiles, and submarines, in the Firth of Clyde's Holy Loch.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Public protests from CND campaigners proved futile.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Royal Navy successfully convinced the government to allow the base because it wanted its own Polaris submarines, and it obtained them in 1963.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The RN's nuclear submarine base opened with four *Resolution*-class Polaris submarines at the expanded Faslane Naval Base on the Gare Loch.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The first patrol of a Trident-armed submarine occurred in 1994, although the US base was closed at the end of the Cold War.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A single front-line Royal Air Force base is located in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] RAF Lossiemouth, located in Moray, is the most northerly air defence fighter base in the United Kingdom and is home to four Eurofighter Typhoon combat aircraft squadrons, three Poseidon MRA1 squadrons, and a full–time, permanently based RAF Regiment squadron.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] An additional four RAF Reserve Squadrons are based in Scotland – 612 Squadron, 2622 (Highland) Squadron and 602 Squadron in Glasgow, and 603 Squadron in Edinburgh.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scots law has a basis derived from Roman law, combining features of both uncodified civil law, dating back to the *Corpus Juris Civilis*, and common law with medieval sources.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The terms of the Treaty of Union with England in 1707 guaranteed the continued existence of a separate legal system in Scotland from that of England and Wales.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Prior to 1611, there were several regional law systems in Scotland, most notably Udal law in Orkney and Shetland, based on old Norse law.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Various other systems derived from common Celtic or Brehon laws survived in the Highlands until the 1800s.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scots law provides for three types of courts responsible for the administration of justice: civil, criminal and heraldic.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The supreme civil court is the Court of Session, although civil appeals can be taken to the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom (or before 1 October 2009, the House of Lords).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The High Court of Justiciary is the supreme criminal court in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Court of Session is housed at Parliament House, in Edinburgh, which was the home of the pre-Union Parliament of Scotland with the High Court of Justiciary and the Supreme Court of Appeal currently located at the Lawnmarket.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The sheriff court is the main criminal and civil court, hearing most cases.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There are 49 sheriff courts throughout the country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] District courts were introduced in 1975 for minor offences and small claims.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] These were gradually replaced by Justice of the Peace Courts from 2008 to 2010.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] For three centuries the Scots legal system was unique for being the only national legal system without a parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] This ended with the advent of the Scottish Parliament in 1999, which legislates for devolved matters.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Many features within the system have been preserved.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Within criminal law, the Scots legal system is unique in having three possible verdicts: "guilty", "not guilty" and "*not proven*".
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Both "not guilty" and "not proven" result in an acquittal, typically with no possibility of retrial per the rule of double jeopardy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A retrial can hear new evidence at a later date that might have proven conclusive in the earlier trial at first instance, where the person acquitted subsequently admits the offence or where it can be proved that the acquittal was tainted by an attempt to pervert the course of justice.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scots juries, sitting in criminal cases, consist of fifteen jurors, which is three more than is typical in many countries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Lord Advocate is the chief legal officer of the Scottish Government and the Crown in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Lord Advocate is the head of the systems in Scotland for the investigation and prosecution of crime, the investigation of deaths as well as serving as the principal legal adviser to the Scottish Government and representing the government in legal proceedings.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] They are the chief public prosecutor for Scotland and all prosecutions on indictment are conducted by the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service in the Lord Advocate's name on behalf of the Monarch.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The officeholder is one of the Great Officers of State of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The current Lord Advocate, Dorothy Bain, was nominated by first minister Nicola Sturgeon, and was appointed in June 2021.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Lord Advocate is supported by the Solicitor General for Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Since 2013, Scotland has had a unified police force known as Police Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Prison Service (SPS) manages the prisons in Scotland, which collectively house over 8,500 prisoners.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Cabinet Secretary for Justice is responsible for the Scottish Prison Service within the Scottish Government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland has a Western-style open mixed economy, considered one of the leading financial centres in Europe, and is the largest financial centre in the United Kingdom outside of London.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Edinburgh is the financial services centre of Scotland, with large finance firms based there including Lloyds Banking Group, the Bank of Scotland, the Royal Bank of Scotland and Standard Life.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Edinburgh was ranked 15th in the Global Financial Centres Index in 2007, and in 2024 was ranked 33rd internationally and 10th across Europe.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Glasgow, Scotland's largest city, also ranks as a significant financial centre in the country, ranked 42nd internationally in 2024 and is widely regarded as an established economic player with particular strengths in domestic expertise.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland is ranked within the top 10 of the largest European regions for foreign direct investment, and is rated as one "of the most promising investment destinations in Europe".
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2024, Scotland's gross domestic product (GDP), including offshore oil and gas, was estimated at £223.4 billion.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2021, Scottish exports in goods and services (excluding intra-UK trade) were estimated to be £50.1 billion.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's primary goods exports are mineral fuels, machinery and transport, and beverages and tobacco.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The country's largest export markets in goods are the Netherlands (£6.9 billion), the United States (£4.0 billion), the Republic of Ireland (£2.8 billion), Germany (£2.8 billion), France (£2.3 billion) and China (£0.8 billion).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Its largest international export market is the European Union.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotch whisky is one of Scotland's more known goods of economic activity.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2024, whisky exports from Scotland contributed £5.4 billion in revenue towards the economy, accounting for 74% of all Scottish food and drink exports internationally in 2023.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scotch whisky industry supports over 41,000 jobs in the sector across Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A considerable number of Scottish companies have established international reputations and trade worldwide in a variety of sectors, including Rockstar North (gaming), Pringle of Scotland and Lyle & Scott (fashion and textiles), A.G.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Barr (soft drinks manufacturing), Alexander Dennis (bus manufacturing), Stagecoach Group (transportation), Tunnock's (confectionery) and Johnnie Walker (whisky).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland was one of the industrial powerhouses of Europe from the time of the Industrial Revolution onwards, being a world leader in manufacturing.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] This left a legacy in the diversity of goods and services which Scotland produces, from textiles, whisky and shortbread to jet engines, buses, computer software, investment management and other related financial services.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In common with most other advanced industrialised economies, Scotland has seen a decline in the importance of both manufacturing industries and primary-based extractive industries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] This has been combined with a rise in the service sector of the economy, which has grown to be the largest sector in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Historically, the Scottish economy was dominated by heavy industry underpinned by shipbuilding in Glasgow, coal mining and steel industries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Petroleum-related industries associated with the extraction of North Sea oil have also been important employers since the 1970s, especially in the north-east of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] De-industrialisation during the 1970s and 1980s saw a shift from a manufacturing focus towards a more service-oriented economy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's fisheries sector and associated zone is the fourth largest amongst European nations.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Tourism and major international events are regarded as one of the countries most important sectors of industry, supporting over 245,000 related jobs across the sector and contributing £10.8 billion in revenue in 2023, 6% of the overall Scottish economy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The most visited tourist attractions in the country include Edinburgh Castle, the National Museum of Scotland, the Battle of Culloden Visitor Centre, Edinburgh Zoo, Stirling Castle and Urquhart Castle.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Tourist Boards (Scotland) Act 2006 established VisitScotland, the executive agency of the Scottish Government responsible for tourism across the country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] An international poll conducted in 2023 ranked Scotland's landscape 7th out of 60 countries, whilst it scored 72.3% for tourism.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Edinburgh Castle and the National Museum of Scotland are amongst the most popular attractions in the country, with both receiving over 2 million visitors in 2017.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Over 4 million people visited Scotland in 2023, an increase of 15% since 2019.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Attractions such as Loch Lomond, The Kelpies and the mythical Loch Ness Monster attracted visitors primarily from North America.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The majority of international visitors to Scotland are primarily from the United States, Germany, Canada and Australia.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Its coastline, beaches, castles, ancient heritage and cultural attractions have made Scotland one of the most popular destinations in Europe.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2016, expenditure from international tourism accounted £9.7 billion of the Scottish economy.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Although the Bank of England is the central bank for the UK, three Scottish clearing banks issue Sterling banknotes: the Bank of Scotland, the Royal Bank of Scotland and the Clydesdale Bank.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Bank of Scotland was the first bank in Europe to successfully print its own paper currency, with the new banknotes entering circulation in 1696, making the Bank of Scotland the longest continuous issuer of banknotes in the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Prior to the 2008 financial crisis, Scotland ranked second only to London in the European league of headquarters locations of the 30 largest banks in Europe as measured by market value.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The issuing of banknotes by retail banks in Scotland is subject to the Banking Act 2009, which repealed all earlier legislation under which banknote issuance was regulated, and the Scottish and Northern Ireland Banknote Regulations 2009.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The value of the Scottish banknotes in circulation in 2013 was £3.8 billion, underwritten by the Bank of England using funds deposited by each clearing bank, under the Banking Act 2009, to cover the total value of such notes in circulation.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland has five international airports operating scheduled services to Europe, North America and Asia, as well as domestic services to England, Northern Ireland and Wales and within Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Edinburgh Airport is currently Scotland's busiest airport, handling over 13 million passengers in 2017.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] It is also the UK's 6th busiest airport.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The airline Loganair has its headquarters at Glasgow Airport and markets itself as *Scotland's Airline*.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Network Rail owns and operates the fixed infrastructure assets of the railway system in Scotland, while the Scottish Government retains overall responsibility for rail strategy and funding in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's rail network has 359 railway stations and around 1,710 miles (2,760 km) of track.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2022–23 there were 64 million passenger journeys on ScotRail rail services.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] On 1 January 2006, Transport Scotland was established, which would oversee the regulation of railways in Scotland and administer major rail projects.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Since April 2022, Transport Scotland has taken ScotRail back into public ownership via its operator of last resort, Scottish Rail Holdings.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] It did the same with the Caledonian Sleeper service in June 2023.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Glasgow Subway is the only underground system in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] It opened on 14 December 1896, making it the third-oldest underground network in the world after the Budapest Metro and the London Underground.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] It is owned and operated by Strathclyde Partnership for Transport.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish motorways and major trunk roads are managed by Transport Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The remainder of the road network is managed by the Scottish local authorities in each of their areas.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Regular ferry services operate between the Scottish mainland and outlying islands.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Ferries serving both the Inner and Outer Hebrides are principally operated by the state-owned enterprise Caledonian MacBrayne.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Services to the Northern Isles are operated by Serco.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Other routes, such as southwest Scotland to Northern Ireland, are served by multiple companies.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] DFDS Seaways operated a freight-only Rosyth – Zeebrugge ferry service, until a fire damaged the vessel DFDS were using.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A passenger service was also operated between 2002 and 2010.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] demonstrated the first working television system on 26 January 1926.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's primary sources of energy are provided through renewable energy (61.8%), nuclear (25.7%) and fossil fuel generation (10.9%).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Whitelee Wind Farm is the largest onshore wind farm in the United Kingdom, and was Europe's largest onshore wind farm for some time.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Tidal power is an emerging source of energy in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The MeyGen tidal stream energy plant in the north of the country is claimed to be the largest tidal stream energy project in the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In Scotland, 98.6% of all electricity used was from renewable sources.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Between October 2021 and September 2022 63.1% of all electricity generated in Scotland was from renewable sources, 83.6% was classed as low carbon and 14.5% was from fossil fuels.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Government has a target to have the equivalent of 50% of the energy for Scotland's heat, transport and electricity consumption to be supplied from renewable sources by 2030.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] They have stated that, in 2022, the equivalent of 113% of the country's overall electrical consumption was produced by renewable energy, making it the highest recorded figure of renewable energy generated to date.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's inventions and discoveries are said to have revolutionised human technology and have played a major role in the creation of the modern world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Such inventions – the television, the telephone, refrigerators, the MRI scanner, flushing toilets and the steam engine – are said to have been possible by Scotland's universities and parish schools, together with the commitment Scots had to education during the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Alexander Fleming is responsible for the discovery of the world's first broadly effective antibiotic substance, which he named penicillin, earning him a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1945.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Modern Scottish inventions – the Falkirk Wheel and the Glasgow Tower – hold world records for being the only rotating boat lift and the tallest fully rotating freestanding structure in the world respectively.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's space industry is a world leader in sustainable space technology, and, according to the UK Space Agency, there are 173 space companies currently operating in Scotland as of May 2021.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] These include spacecraft manufacturers, launch providers, downstream data analysers, and research organisations.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The space industry in Scotland is projected to generate £2billion in income for Scotland's space cluster by 2030.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scottish space industry jobs represent almost one in five of all UK space industry employment.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In addition to its space industry, Scotland is home to two planned spaceports – Sutherland spaceport and SaxaVord Spaceport.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] During the 1820s, many Scots migrated from Scotland to countries such as Australia, the United States and Canada, principally from the Highlands which remained poor in comparison to elsewhere in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Highlands was the only part of mainland Britain with a recurrent famine.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A small range of products were exported from the region, which had negligible industrial production and a continued population growth that tested the subsistence agriculture.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] These problems, and the desire to improve agriculture and profits were the driving forces of the ongoing Highland Clearances, in which many of the population of the Highlands suffered eviction as lands were enclosed, principally so that they could be used for sheep farming.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The first phase of the clearances followed patterns of agricultural change throughout Britain.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The second phase was driven by overpopulation, the Highland Potato Famine and the collapse of industries that had relied on the wartime economy of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Even with the development of industry, there were not enough good jobs.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As a result, during the period 1841–1931, about 2 million Scots migrated to North America and Australia, and another 750,000 Scots relocated to England.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Caused by the advent of refrigeration and imports of lamb, mutton and wool from overseas, the 1870s brought with them a collapse of sheep prices and an abrupt halt in the previous sheep farming boom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland is the most sparsely populated country of the United Kingdom.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In August 2012, the Scottish population reached an all-time high of 5.25 million people.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The reasons given were that, in Scotland, births were outnumbering the number of deaths, and immigrants were moving to Scotland from overseas.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2011, 43,700 people moved from Wales, Northern Ireland or England to live in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The most recent census in Scotland was conducted by the Scottish Government and the National Records of Scotland in March 2022.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The population of Scotland at the 2022 Census was 5,436,600, the highest ever, beating the previous record of 5,295,400 at the 2011 Census.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In the 2011 Census, 62% of Scotland's population stated their national identity as 'Scottish only', 18% as 'Scottish and British', 8% as 'British only', and 4% chose 'other identity only'.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Throughout its history, Scotland has long had a tradition of migration from Scotland and immigration into Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2021, the Scottish Government released figures showing that an estimated 41,000 people had immigrated from other international countries into Scotland, while an average of 22,100 people had migrated from Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scottish Government data from 2002 shows that by 2021, there had been a sharp increase in immigration to Scotland, with 2002 estimates standing at 27,800 immigrants.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] While immigration had increased from 2002, migration from Scotland had dropped, with 2002 estimates standing at 26,200 people migrating from Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Although Edinburgh is the capital of Scotland, the largest city is Glasgow, which has just over 584,000 inhabitants.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Greater Glasgow conurbation, with a population of almost 1.2 million, is home to nearly a quarter of Scotland's population.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Central Belt is where most of the main towns and cities of Scotland are located, including Glasgow, Edinburgh, Dundee, and Perth.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's only major city outside the Central Belt is Aberdeen.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish Lowlands host 80% of the total population, where the Central Belt accounts for 3.5 million people.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In general, only the more accessible and larger islands remain inhabited.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Currently, fewer than 90 remain inhabited.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Southern Uplands is essentially rural and dominated by agriculture and forestry.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Because of housing problems in Glasgow and Edinburgh, five new towns were designated between 1947 and 1966.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] They are East Kilbride, Glenrothes, Cumbernauld, Livingston, and Irvine.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The largest council area by population is Glasgow City, with Highland being the largest in terms of geographical area.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland has four indigenous languages: English, Scots, Scottish Gaelic, and British Sign Language.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scottish Standard English, a variety of English as spoken in Scotland, is at one end of a bipolar linguistic continuum, with broad Scots at the other.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scottish Standard English may have been influenced to varying degrees by Scots.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Highland English is spoken in that region, while Gaelic is mostly spoken in the Western Isles, where it continues to be used by a large proportion of residents.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Overall, the use of Scotland's indigenous languages other than English has declined since the 19th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The 2011 census indicated that 63% of the population had "no skills in Scots".
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The use of Gaelic is confined to 1% of the population.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The number of Gaelic speakers in Scotland dropped from 250,000 in 1881 to 60,000 in 2008.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Across the whole of Scotland, the 2011 census showed that 25,000 people (0.49% of the population) used Gaelic at home.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In the 21st century, moves were made to provide official support to these languages, beginning with formal recognition as minority languages and culminating in both Scots and Gaelic being given official status in Scotland in 2025.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The most common language spoken at home in Scotland after English and Scots is Polish, with about 1.1% of the population, or 54,000 people.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Immigration since World War II has given Glasgow, Edinburgh, and Dundee small South Asian communities.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2011, there were an estimated 49,000 ethnically Pakistani people living in Scotland, making them the largest non-White ethnic group.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The 2004 enlargement of the European Union spurred an increase in migration from Central and Eastern Europe to Scotland, and the 2011 census indicated that 61,000 Poles lived there.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There are many more people with Scottish ancestry living abroad than the total population of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In the 2000 Census, 9.2 million Americans self-reported some degree of Scottish descent.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Ulster's Protestant population is mainly of Lowland Scottish descent, and it is estimated that there are more than 27 million descendants of the Scots-Irish migration now living in the US.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In Canada, the Scottish-Canadian community accounts for 4.7 million people.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] About 20% of the original European settler population of New Zealand came from Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] As per the 2022 Census, a majority of Scots (51.12%) reported not following any religion.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The most practiced religion is Christianity (38.79%), mostly the Church of Scotland (20.36%) and Roman Catholicism (13.3%).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In almost every council area, the most common response to the census question was "No religion," except in Na h-Eileanan Siar and Inverclyde, where the Church of Scotland (35.3%) and Catholicism (33.4%) were the most common responses, respectively.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Forms of Christianity have dominated religious life in what is now Scotland for more than 1,400 years.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Since the Scottish Reformation of 1560, the national church (the Church of Scotland, also known as The Kirk) has been Protestant in orientation and Reformed in theology.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Since 1689 it has had a Presbyterian system of church government independent from the state.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Its membership dropped just below 300,000 in 2020 (5% of the total population) The Church operates a territorial parish structure, with every community in Scotland having a local congregation.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland also has a significant Roman Catholic population with 13.3% professing that faith, particularly in Greater Glasgow and the north-west.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] After the Reformation, Roman Catholicism in Scotland continued in the Highlands and some western islands like Uist and Barra, and it was strengthened during the 19th century by immigration from Ireland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Other Christian denominations in Scotland include the Free Church of Scotland, and various other Presbyterian offshoots.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's third largest church is the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Other minority faiths include Islam (2.2%), Hinduism (0.55%), Sikhism and Buddhism.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Samyé Ling monastery near Eskdalemuir, which celebrated its 40th anniversary in 2007, is the oldest Buddhist monastery in Western Europe.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The Scottish education system has always had a characteristic emphasis on a broad education.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In the Reformation, the 1560 *First Book of Discipline* set out a plan for a school in every parish, but this proved financially impossible.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 1616 an act in Privy council commanded every parish to establish a school.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] By the late seventeenth century there was a largely complete network of parish schools in the lowlands, but in the Highlands basic education was still lacking in many areas.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Education remained a matter for the church rather than the state until the Education (Scotland) Act 1872.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Education in Scotland is the responsibility of the Scottish Government and is overseen by its executive agency Education Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The *Curriculum for Excellence*, Scotland's national school curriculum, presently provides the curricular framework for children and young people from age 3 to 18.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] All 3- and 4-year-old children in Scotland are entitled to a free nursery place.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Formal primary education begins at approximately 5 years old and lasts for 7 years (P1–P7); children in Scotland study National Qualifications of the Curriculum for Excellence between the ages of 14 and 18.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The school leaving age is 16, after which students may choose to remain at school and study further qualifications.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] A small number of students at certain private schools may follow the English system and study towards GCSEs and A and AS-Levels instead.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] There are fifteen Scottish universities, some of which are among the oldest in the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland had more universities per capita in QS' World University Rankings' top 100 in 2012 than any other nation.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The country produces 1% of the world's published research with less than 0.1% of the world's population, and higher education institutions account for 9% of Scotland's service sector exports.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Scotland's University Courts are the only bodies in Scotland authorised to award degrees.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Health care in Scotland is mainly provided by NHS Scotland, Scotland's public health care system.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] This was founded by the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1947 (later repealed by the National Health Service (Scotland) Act 1978) that took effect on 5 July 1948 to coincide with the launch of the NHS in England and Wales.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Prior to 1948, half of Scotland's landmass was already covered by state-funded health care, provided by the Highlands and Islands Medical Service.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Healthcare policy and funding is the responsibility of the Scottish Government's Health Directorates.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] In 2014, the NHS in Scotland had around 140,000 staff.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The total fertility rate (TFR) in Scotland is below the replacement rate of 2.1 (the TFR was 1.73 in 2011).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The majority of births are to unmarried women (51.3% of births were outside of marriage in 2012).
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Life expectancy for those born in Scotland between 2012 and 2014 is 77.1 years for males and 81.1 years for females.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] This is the lowest of any of the four countries of the UK.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] The number of hospital admissions in Scotland for diseases such as cancer was 2,528 in 2002.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Over the next ten years, by 2012, this had increased to 2,669.
[src:scotland/scotland-p02] Hospital admissions for other diseases, such as coronary heart disease (CHD) were lower, with 727 admissions in 2002, and decreasing to 489 in 2012.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has seven World Heritage Sites – St.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Kilda, Edinburgh Old Town and New Town, The Heart of Neolithic Orkney, New Lanark, The Antonine Wall, The Forth Bridge and The Flow Country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Zenith of Iron Age Shetland is currently a candidate for World Heritage Site status from UNESCO.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Historic Environment Scotland is responsible for 'cultural' sites as part of their wider responsibility towards the historic environment.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Environment Directorate is responsible for natural sites.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] As one of the Celtic nations, Scotland and Scottish culture are represented at inter-Celtic events at home and over the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland hosts several music festivals including Celtic Connections (Glasgow), and the Hebridean Celtic Festival (Stornoway).
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Festivals celebrating Celtic culture, such as Festival Interceltique de Lorient (Brittany), the Pan Celtic Festival (Ireland), and the National Celtic Festival (Portarlington, Australia), feature elements of Scottish culture such as language, music and dance.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has a literary heritage dating back to the early Middle Ages.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The earliest extant literature composed in what is now Scotland was in Brythonic speech in the 6th century, but is preserved as part of Welsh literature.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Later medieval literature included works in Latin, Gaelic, Old English and French.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The first surviving major text in Early Scots is the 14th-century poet John Barbour's epic *Brus*, focusing on the life of Robert I, and was soon followed by a series of vernacular romances and prose works.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In the 16th century, the crown's patronage helped the development of Scots drama and poetry, but the accession of James VI to the English throne removed a major centre of literary patronage and Scots was sidelined as a literary language.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Interest in Scots literature was revived in the 18th century by figures including James Macpherson, whose Ossian Cycle made him the first Scottish poet to gain an international reputation and was a major influence on the European Enlightenment.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] It was also a major influence on Robert Burns, whom many consider the national poet, and Walter Scott, whose Waverley Novels did much to define Scottish identity in the 19th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Towards the end of the Victorian era a number of Scottish-born authors achieved international reputations as writers in English, including Robert Louis Stevenson, Arthur Conan Doyle, J.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In the 20th century the Scottish Renaissance saw a surge of literary activity and attempts to reclaim the Scots language as a medium for serious literature.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Members of the movement were followed by a new generation of post-war poets including Edwin Morgan, who would be appointed the first Makar by the Scottish Government in 2004.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Sorley MacLean was described by the Scottish Poetry Library as "one of the major Scottish poets of the modern era" because of his "mastery of his chosen medium and his engagement with the European poetic tradition and European politics".
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Nobel Prize Laureate Seamus Heaney credited MacLean with saving Scottish Gaelic poetry.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] From the 1980s Scottish literature enjoyed another major revival, particularly associated with a group of writers including Irvine Welsh.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scottish poets who emerged in the same period included Carol Ann Duffy, who, in May 2009, was the first Scot named the monarch's Poet Laureate.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland's national poet is known as the Makar and is appointed by the first minister to promote literacy, writing and poetry across the country, as well as to produce work for national events and produce annual reports to the government.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The incumbent Makar is Pàdraig MacAoidh, the first Scottish Gaelic writer to hold the position.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] National newspapers such as the *Daily Record*, *The Herald*, *The Scotsman* and *The National* are all produced in Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Important regional dailies include the Evening News in Edinburgh, *The Courier* in Dundee in the east, and *The Press and Journal* serving Aberdeen and the north.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland is represented at the Celtic Media Festival, which showcases film and television from the Celtic countries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scottish entrants have won many awards since the festival began in 1980.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland's national broadcaster is BBC Scotland, a division of the BBC, which runs three national television stations, BBC One Scotland, BBC Scotland and the Gaelic-language BBC Alba, and the national radio stations, *BBC Radio Scotland* and *BBC Radio nan Gàidheal*.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The main Scottish commercial television station is STV which broadcasts on two of the three ITV regions of Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland's film industry is supported by Screen Scotland, the executive non-departmental public body of the Scottish Government which provides funding and support for film production in the country.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scottish music is a significant aspect of the nation's culture, with both traditional and modern influences.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] A famous traditional Scottish instrument is the Great Highland bagpipe, a woodwind reed instrument consisting of three drones and a melody pipe (called the chanter), which are fed continuously by a reservoir of air in a bag.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The popularity of pipe bands—primarily featuring bagpipes, various types of snares and drums, and showcasing Scottish traditional dress and music—has spread throughout the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Bagpipes are featured in holiday celebrations, parades, funerals, weddings, and other events internationally.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Many military regiments have a pipe band of their own.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In addition to the Great Highland pipes, several smaller, somewhat quieter bellows-blown varieties of bagpipe are played in Scotland, including the smallpipes and the Border pipes.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scottish popular music has gained an international following, with artists such as Lewis Capaldi, Amy Macdonald, KT Tunstall, Nina Nesbitt, Chvrches, Gerry Cinnamon and Paolo Nutini gaining international success.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] DJ Calvin Harris was one of the most streamed artists on Spotify in 2023, whilst Susan Boyle's debut album was one of the best-selling albums of the 21st century, and was the best-selling album internationally in 2009.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Runrig popularised Celtic rock and frequently performed in Scottish Gaelic, with their 1995 single "An Ubhal as Àirde" the first song in the language to reach the UK Top 20.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Musical talent in Scotland is recognised via the Scottish Music Awards, Scottish Album of the Year Award, the Scots Trad Music Awards and the BBC Radio Scotland Young Traditional Musician award.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scottish cuisine has distinctive attributes and recipes of its own but shares much with wider British and European cuisine as a result of local and foreign influences, both ancient and modern.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Traditional Scottish dishes exist alongside international foodstuffs brought about by migration.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland's natural larder of game, dairy products, fish, fruit, and vegetables is the chief factor in traditional Scots cooking, with a high reliance on simplicity and a lack of spices from abroad, as these were historically rare and expensive.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Irn-Bru is the most common Scottish carbonated soft drink, often described as "Scotland's other national drink" (after whisky).
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] During the Late Middle Ages and early modern era, French cuisine played a role in Scottish cookery due to cultural exchanges brought about by the "Auld Alliance", especially during the reign of Mary, Queen of Scots.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Mary, on her return to Scotland, brought an entourage of French staff who are considered responsible for revolutionising Scots cooking and for some of Scotland's unique food terminology.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has its own national governing bodies, such as the Scottish Football Association (the second oldest national football association in the world) and the Scottish Rugby Union.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Variations of football have been played in Scotland for centuries, with the earliest reference dating back to 1424.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The world's first official international association football match, between Scotland and England was held in Glasgow on 30 November 1872, and resulted in a 0–0 draw.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Scottish Cup was first contested in 1873, and is the oldest trophy in association football.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Scottish Football Association (SFA) is the main governing body for Scottish association football, and a founding member of the International Football Association Board (IFAB) which governs the Laws of the Game.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland is one of only four countries to have a permanent representative on the IFAB; the other four representatives being appointed for set periods by FIFA.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The SFA has responsibility for the Scotland national football team and the Scotland women's team.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] With the modern game of golf originating in 15th-century Scotland, the country is promoted as the home of golf.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] To many golfers the Old Course in the Fife town of St Andrews, an ancient links course dating to before 1552, is considered a site of pilgrimage.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In 1764, the standard 18-hole golf course was created at St Andrews when members modified the course from 22 to 18 holes.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The world's oldest golf tournament, and golf's first major, is The Open Championship, which was first played on 17 October 1860 at Prestwick Golf Club, in Ayrshire, Scotland, with Scottish golfers winning the earliest majors.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] There are many other famous golf courses in Scotland, including Carnoustie, Gleneagles, Muirfield, and Royal Troon.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Scottish Rugby Union is the second oldest rugby union in the world.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Murrayfield Stadium in Edinburgh is the national stadium of the Scottish national rugby team.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Scotland rugby team played their first official test match, winning 1–0 against England at Raeburn Place in 1871.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has competed in the Six Nations from the inaugural tournament in 1883, winning it 14 times outright—including the last Five Nations in 1999—and sharing it another 8 times.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Rugby World Cup was introduced in 1987 and Scotland have competed in all nine competitions, the most recent being in the 2023 Rugby World Cup.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland competes with the England rugby team annually for the Calcutta Cup.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Each year, this fixture is played out as part of the Six Nations, with Scotland having last won in 2026.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Other distinctive features of the national sporting culture include the Highland games, curling and shinty.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In boxing, Scotland has had 13 world champions, including Ken Buchanan, Benny Lynch and Jim Watt.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has also been successful in motorsport, particularly in Formula One.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Notable drivers include; David Coulthard, Jim Clark, Paul Di Resta, and Jackie Stewart.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In IndyCar, Dario Franchitti has won 4 consecutive IndyCar world championships.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has competed at every Commonwealth Games since 1930 and has won 356 medals in total—91 Gold, 104 Silver and 161 Bronze.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has hosted the Commonwealth Games three times – Edinburgh played host to the Commonwealth Games in 1970 and 1986, and most recently Glasgow in 2014.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Glasgow was confirmed as the host city for the 2026 Commonwealth Games in September 2024.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Edinburgh was the host city for the inaugural Commonwealth Youth Games in 2000.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Andrew, martyred while bound to an X-shaped cross, first appeared in the Kingdom of Scotland during the reign of William I.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Following the death of King Alexander III in 1286 an image of Andrew was used on the seal of the Guardians of Scotland who assumed control of the kingdom during the subsequent interregnum.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Use of a simplified symbol associated with Saint Andrew, the saltire, has its origins in the late 14th century; the Parliament of Scotland decreeing in 1385 that Scottish soldiers should wear a white Saint Andrew's Cross on the front and back of their tunics.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Use of a blue background for the Saint Andrew's Cross is said to date from at least the 15th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Since 1606 the saltire has also formed part of the design of the Union Flag.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Highlanders can thank James Graham, 3rd Duke of Montrose, for the repeal in 1782 of the Dress Act 1746, which prohibited the wearing of tartans.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Scotland has its own regalia known as the Honours of Scotland (informally the Scottish Crown Jewels) which consists of the Crown of Scotland, a Sceptre and Scottish Sword of State.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Scottish crown was worn by Scottish monarchs during their coronation, and today is kept in the Crown Room at Edinburgh Castle.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Crown of Scotland is present at each state opening of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Collectively, the Honours of Scotland are the oldest regalia in the British Isles, dating from the late 15th and early 16th centuries.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Other currently less popular candidates for the National Anthem of Scotland include *Scotland the Brave*, *Highland Cathedral*, *Scots Wha Hae* and *A Man's A Man for A' That*.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] St Andrew's Day, 30 November, is the national day, although Burns' Night tends to be more widely observed, particularly outside Scotland.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] In 2006, the Scottish Parliament passed the St Andrew's Day Bank Holiday (Scotland) Act 2007, designating the day an official bank holiday.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] Tartan Day is a recent innovation from Canada.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The national animal of Scotland is the unicorn, which has been a Scottish heraldic symbol since the 12th century.
[src:scotland/scotland-p03] The Court of the Lord Lyon regulates Scottish heraldry and the Public Register of All Armorial Bearings in Scotland.
[src:scotland/uk] In October 1984, RFC 920 set out the creation of ccTLDs using country codes derived from the corresponding two-letter code in the ISO 3166-1 list.
[src:scotland/uk] However, the UK academic network Name Registration Scheme, JANET NRS, had defined "UK" as the top-level domain a few months before the compilation of the ISO-derived list.
[src:scotland/uk] Consequently, .uk was chosen and registered on 24 July 1985. .gb was reserved but never widely used and it is no longer possible to register domains under that ccTLD.
[src:scotland/uk] As with other ccTLDs in the early days it was originally delegated by Jon Postel to a "trusted person" to manage.
[src:scotland/uk] Andrew McDowell at UCL was assigned .uk, the first country code delegation.
[src:scotland/uk] In time, he passed it to Willie Black at the UK Education and Research Networking Association (UKERNA).
[src:scotland/uk] Originally, domain requests were emailed, manually screened by and then forwarded to the UK Naming Committee before being processed by UKERNA.
[src:scotland/uk] Membership of this committee was restricted to a group of high-end ISPs who were part of a formal peering arrangement.
[src:scotland/uk] The Naming Committee was organised as a mailing list to which all proposed names were circulated.
[src:scotland/uk] The members would consider the proposals under a ruleset that insisted that all domain names should be very close if not identical to a registered business name of the registrant.
[src:scotland/uk] Members of the Naming Committee could object to any name, and if at least a small number of objections were received, the name was refused.
[src:scotland/uk] By the mid-1990s the growth of the Internet, and particularly the advent of the World Wide Web was pushing requests for domain name registrations up to levels that were not manageable by a group of part-time volunteers.
[src:scotland/uk] Oliver Smith of Demon Internet forced the issue by providing the committee with a series of automated tools, called the "automaton", which formalised and automated the naming process end to end.
[src:scotland/uk] This allowed many more registrations to be processed far more reliably and rapidly, and inspired individuals such as Ivan Pope to explore more entrepreneurial approaches to registration.
[src:scotland/uk] Various plans were put forward for the possible management of the domain, mostly Internet service providers seeking to stake a claim, each of which were naturally unacceptable to the rest of the committee.
[src:scotland/uk] In response to this Black, as the .uk Name, stepped up with a bold proposal for a not-for-profit commercial entity to deal with the .uk domain properly.
[src:scotland/uk] Commercial interests initially balked at this, but with widespread support Nominet UK was formed in 1996 to be the .uk Network Information Centre, a role which it continues to this day.
[src:scotland/uk] The general form of the rules (i.e. which domains can be registered and whether to allow second level domains) was set by the Naming Committee.
[src:scotland/uk] Nominet has not made major changes to the rules, although it has introduced a new second level domain .me.uk for individuals.
[src:scotland/uk] Until 10 June 2014 it was not possible to register a domain name directly under .uk (such as *internet.uk*); it was only possible as a third-level domain (such as *internet.co.uk*).
[src:scotland/uk] Currently, management of the .uk domain name is delegated by IANA to Nominet UK.
[src:scotland/uk] It is possible to directly register a domain name with Nominet UK at £80+VAT as of 2021, but it is faster and cheaper to do it via a Nominet-accredited domain registrar costing in the region of £10+VAT in 2021.
[src:scotland/uk] If a domain was registered before 23:59 UTC on 28 October 2013 the user had the rights to the equivalent .uk domain (providing there was no other corresponding .co.uk, .org.uk, me.uk, .ltd.uk, .plc.uk or .net.uk registered).
[src:scotland/uk] For example, if "your-company.co.uk" was held since 2 October 2013, the registrant of 'your-company.co.uk' had the reserved right of registering "your-company.uk", up until 06:00 BST on 25 June 2019.
[src:scotland/uk] 123-reg and NamesCo both created such domains for their customers for free but then began demanding payment in September 2019.
[src:scotland/uk] .co.uk, .ltd.uk, .me.uk, .net.uk, .nic.uk, .org.uk, .plc.uk and .sch.uk are managed by Nominet UK and except for .nic.uk are available for registration by the public (though they all carry various degrees of restrictions).
[src:scotland/uk] Other second-level domains are managed by various government agencies, and generally more strongly controlled.
[src:scotland/uk] Allocations are on a strict first-come, first-served basis to qualified applicants.
[src:scotland/uk] There are no territorial restrictions: applicants need not have any connection to the UK other than those outlined below for .ltd.uk and other restricted domains.
[src:scotland/uk] .co.uk is by far the most used of the domains, followed by .org.uk then .me.uk. .plc.uk and .ltd.uk are only rarely used.
[src:scotland/uk] The number of new registrations for each of the different .uk domains on a month by month basis can be seen on the Nominet UK website.
[src:scotland/uk] The intended restriction of .co.uk to companies is purely nominal; in practice it is open to any and all applicants.
[src:scotland/uk] Likewise, whilst .org.uk is for organisations, there are no restrictions on registering domains.
[src:scotland/uk] While .me.uk originally had no restrictions on registrants it has since been tightened up to require registrants to be natural persons (i.e. not companies, etc.).
[src:scotland/uk] However, registrants in .ltd.uk must be, and remain, private limited companies incorporated under the UK Companies Acts.
[src:scotland/uk] In addition, names can only be registered if they correspond (in accordance with the algorithm in the rules of registration) with the exact company name, as recorded at the companies registry at Companies House.
[src:scotland/uk] The same conditions apply for public limited companies which wish to use a .plc.uk domain name.
[src:scotland/uk] Neither of these domains is widely used.
[src:scotland/uk] .net.uk is more open, but the Nominet regulations still mean that a registrant must be an ISP, or a similar body, and that the domain is not used for providing services to end-users. .nic.uk, however, is limited solely to domains operated by Nominet.
[src:scotland/uk] .ac.uk domains are intended for the use of higher education institutions and further education colleges, and are also used by some academic support bodies such as the Universities and Colleges Admissions Service public research establishments, and learned societies such as the Royal Society.
[src:scotland/uk] Primary and secondary education uses .sch.uk.
[src:scotland/uk] Unusually, .sch.uk domains are allocated at the fourth level, with the third level being taken up by the name of the local authority (LA, previously LEA or local education authority) e.g. schoolname.leaname.sch.uk.
[src:scotland/uk] For example, the Little Ilford School in Newham has the domain name littleilford.newham.sch.uk and the West Exe School in Exeter, Devon has the domain name westexe.devon.sch.uk.
[src:scotland/uk] Previously applications were made in the normal way, but after Nominet came to an arrangement with the education authorities, one domain per school was issued automatically.
[src:scotland/uk] Those that had already used another domain were still given one and were able to redirect it to their main domain.
